Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Download: Google's Stock Split a Boon to CIOs
Headlines.Author: Michael Hickins
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Download: Google's Stock Split a Boon to CIOs

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Good morning, and welcome to Friday. The big news this morning is Google's boffo earnings, as WSJ reports. But to CIOs, the announced stock split is more important because it helps preserve the control exercised by co-founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin. In a letter to shareholders, Page writes the split is intended to protect Google management from "outside pressures and the temptation to sacrifice future opportunities to meet short-term demands" and maintain the company's "pioneering spirit."
This means Page, not Wall Street, will decide whether Google will continue investing in ventures like Google Apps or enterprise search, which don't pay off for Google in the short term, but may -- or have -- become an important part of the business technology ecosystem. It's hard to find a CIO these days who isn't testing some portion of Apps within their organization, even if it's only for email, because of the tremendous savings -- and because it's a cudgel to hold over Microsoft's head.

Headlines.Headline: Terex 1Q Profit Down 98% On Prior-Year Gain; Sales Jump

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Terex Corp.'s TEX first-quarter profit slumped 98% absent a big prior-year asset sale gain, although the equipment maker reported sales growth that exceeded Wall Street's expectations and higher gross margins. The company, which makes specialized equipment such as tower cranes and rock crushers, backed its full-year earnings forecast but raised its revenue outlook to $5.2 billion to $5.5 billion, up from the prior view of $5 billion to $5.4 billion. Headlines.Author: E.S. Browning

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Stocks sagged again in the face of more unsettling news, which ranged
from the U.S. air strikes against terrorist bases to a slap at Intel
 from a prominent stock
analyst.The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 81.87, or 0.94%, to 8611.41. That
left it still well above its recent closing low of 8425 a week ago Friday.
As is often the case in times of uncertainty, small stocks took a sharper
blow. The Russell 2000 small-stock index fell 4.11, or 1.01%, to
401.73.In what some traders saw as a flight to quality, bond prices rose,
although the dollar was mixed.Financial stocks were among the hardest-hit, as currency worries spread
to South America. Although Venezuelan officials, in particular, have denied
any intention to devalue their currency, worries have mounted for several
days that Argentina, Brazil and Venezuela all could be caught in the
international currency crisis."People are wondering whether, if Argentina devalues, there will be a
ripple effect where others do it," noted Ned Collins, head of trading at
Daiwa Securities America. The devaluation talk, together with growing
worries about China's currency and weakness in Russian banks, all weighed
on U.S. financials. J.P.
Morgan
, American
Express
 and Travelers
Group
, all components of the Dow industrials, fell sharply.News that former White House intern Monica Lewinsky was testifying again
to a grand jury about the president, together with the U.S. action on
terrorist bases, also made some investors nervous. The early afternoon
announcement that the president was about to make a statement and fly back
to Washington spooked traders."People thought that he was going to resign, and the market went
straight down until people said that it had something to do with national
security. Then it went back up," said Anthony Conroy, head of global
trading at BT Asset Management, the asset-management arm of Bankers
Trust.Oil prices gyrated on the news of the antiterrorist strikes, sending
stocks such as Exxon
, Mobil
 and Texaco
 up.Semiconductor stocks sagged further after Merrill Lynch analyst Thomas
Kurlak downgraded Intel and Texas
Instruments
. He said that, in the face of price competition, Intel
will have trouble maintaining its computer-processor revenues. But other
technology stocks, such as Microsoft
, Dell Computer
, Cisco Systems
 and several Internet
stocks, managed to gain ground.Friday's so-called double witching, the monthly expiration of stock and
stock-index options contracts, also put pressure on stocks.The technology-heavy Nasdaq Composite Index fell 10.24, or 0.56%, to
1832.45. The Philadelphia Semiconductor Index, already weak on Wednesday,
declined another 11.34, or 0.44%, to 245.47. The broad Standard &
Poor's 500-stock index retreated 6.46, or 0.59%, to 1091.60.World-wide, stocks declined in dollar terms. The Dow Jones World Stock
Index fell 1.16 points to 183.54.In major market action:Stocks slumped
. On the Big Board, volume reached 616 million shares, with 1,906
stocks declining and 1,103 advancing.Bonds rose
. The 30-year bellwether Treasury bond was up 20/32 point, or $6.25
per $1,000 bond. Its yield fell to a historic low of 5.509%.The dollar was
mixed
. It was at 1.7991 marks and 143.14 yen, compared with 1.7977 marks
and 144.07 yen late Wednesday in New York.

#text:
No-load fund families are feeling the heat from discount brokerages
    offering "mutual fund supermarkets." Over the past 18 months, several fund
    groups have moved beyond the simple selling of their own mutual fund products and have
    begun offering brokerage and banking services, reported The Wall Street Journal Thursday.
    Many fund companies now sell stocks and bonds, as well as mutual funds from other
    families. The reason for this shift is two-fold. First, no-load groups are losing money to
    supermarket fees. While investors buying no-load funds through

,
    for instance, pay no fees, the fund company must pay a commission to Schwab. The second
    reason is marketing. Purchasers of no-load funds through a supermarket are customers of
    the broker, not the fund company. "It's all about trying to control the
    customer," says fund consultant

, "Fund groups
    that can serve as gateways to other products will get a better shot at keeping a
    customer's assets."

PARAGRAPH.#text:

        of the pioneer Web sites offering stock quotes and
        information for investors is retrenching. Quote.com
        has fired 10 percent of its staff and president Tom
        Henry has resigned after nine months on the job,
        according to News.com. Company founder Chris Cooper
        said, "We found we didn't need to have two leaders.

        the right vision ... Tom came from a background with a
        news focus, and mine was more market focus," the
        report said. Most of the job cuts, eight in all, affected

        quadrupled, requiring cost reductions.
